<br>
Larger scale units would typically be biomass congeneration, wave or sea current generation, wind, and (in tropical climes) OTEC. Whatever combo of technologies are useful per locale would be applied. (&quot;One size fits all&quot;  means it fits nothing right)<br>
<br>
Systems using fossil fuels or exotics, like nuclear fuels, would be astoundingly too expensive for the developing world.<br>
<br>
It is typically only wealthy oil and nat gas countries like saudi arabia that even attempt to do major non-solar desalinization.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://euclid.dne.wvnet.edu/~jvg/Env310/desalinization.html">euclid.dne.wvnet.edu/~jvg...ation.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
An interesting new tech:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.carmelvalley.com/wi/newdesal.html">www.carmelvalley.com/wi/newdesal.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Wind power is a perfect match for desalinization and has been used quite succesfully. It scales from local to regional capacity and it is quite economical. It is probably the killer tech for desal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.desline.com/articoli/4119.pdf">www.desline.com/articoli/4119.pdf</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.managenergy.net/products/R21.htm">www.managenergy.net/products/R21.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
