<br>
Quite right, however most people only tend to think of Nuclear in terms of *electricity* generation. There are plenty of other ways Nuclear can be used. Providing process heating for industry, desalination or even district heating are possibilitys that I like. A particularly good example would be to provide process heating for Oil refinaries which, I believe, currently use a significant amount of their thoughput to provide their process heat. Using nuclear to do this would be like finding a new venazuala in terms of extending reserves not to mention the reduction in atmospheric polution. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The design is village/town scale (which is the appropriate scale in many situations - never scale up when not needed<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->).<br>
<br>
Theres a lot in that re scale BUT to operate a desalination plant you need salty water. In a nice sunny coastal location neither the water or the energy is a problem. Solar ponds etc work great and are relativly inexpensive. However if we are looking at water shortages on the scale sugested millions of people tens or even hundreds of miles inland will need to be supplied with very large amounts of fresh water, for agriculture as well as for drinking. Desalination on a *substantial* industrial scale would be needed to do this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Sytems using fossil fuels or exotics, like nuclear fuels, would be astoundingly too expensive for the developing world.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
(Assuming the rather gloomy prediction is correct) Desalination on a scale to alleviate this would involve engineering and power use on a scale never previously considererd.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Fossil fuels would be completly out of the question. but It might yet prove to be the most practical use of solar energy ever proposed <br>
<br>
(lets face it! for now, at any rate, solar is pretty useless for anything else. I know its frustrating! there is so much energy there but you just cant use it for anything<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :balling --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_klein_1/crying.gif ALT=":balling"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
however any shortfall would *have* to be met with nuclear capability (possibly even fusion) nothing else can provide the amounts of energy nececarry to desalinate on this scale.<br>
<br>
As for the cost, if you don't you die! It's a powerful motivator! I just hope that, if it comes to the choice. people chose nuclear desalination over nuclear war!<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START |I --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tired.gif ALT="|I"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
