RO is reverse osmosis, a process for taking salt out of water by pumping it at HIGH pressure through a semi-permiable membrane.<br>
<br>
RO is typically considered to be more energy efficient that distillation by a fair margin.<br>
<br>
Yales has hit a homerun with the windmill desalinators, in my opinion.<br>
<br>
(I am a bit of a fan of windmills myself.)<br>
<br>
Windmills are well developed these days, and can extract gobs of energy from air.  The huge strike against them is their intermittance, and the unstorable nature of electricity, which makes using windmills in a power grid in any serious level VERY difficult.  (In other words, their exergy is low.  Indeed, low exergy is the problem with ALL the proposed renewables, sadly.)<br>
<br>
However!  Desalinated water IS perfectly storable. <br>
<br>
Feast yer eyes on this monster, for example:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.gepower.com/dhtml/wind/en_us/products/mmw/mmwspecs.jsp">www.gepower.com/dhtml/win...wspecs.jsp</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
To desalinate water, no generator is needed, as yales points out.  Just high pressure and an RO plant.<br>
<br>
When the wind blows hard, you desalinate water like mad and store the excess in a tank.  When the wind stops, you drink the stored water and backflush your RO plant.<br>
<br>
The same theory holds for using windmills to generate hydrogen as a storage mechanism, then burn the hydrogen in co-generation plants that we have built scads of before natgas got so insanely expensive, and get electricity that way.<br>
<br>
HeeHee!  The future is bright, indeed!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
